Blockchain comparison table
| Blockchain | Node types | Clients / software | Consensus |
|---|---|---|---|
| Bitcoin | Full nodes, light nodes, miners | Bitcoin Core | Proof of Work (PoW). :contentReference[oaicite:20]{index=20} |
| Ethereum | Execution clients + Consensus clients, full/light nodes | Geth, Nethermind; Lighthouse, Prysm, Teku | Proof of Stake (PoS) (post-Merge). :contentReference[oaicite:21]{index=21} |
| Solana | Validators, RPC nodes, archival nodes | solana-validator (CLI) | Proof of History (PoH) + PoS (for validator selection). :contentReference[oaicite:22]{index=22} |
| Polkadot | Validators, nominators, collators | polkadot (Substrate clients) | Nominated Proof of Stake (NPoS). :contentReference[oaicite:23]{index=23} |
| Avalanche | Validators, full nodes, RPC nodes | AvalancheGo | Avalanche consensus (sub-sampled voting, fast finality). :contentReference[oaicite:24]{index=24} |

Distributed ledger vs Blockchain
| Feature | Distributed Ledger (DLT) | Blockchain |
|---|---|---|
| Definition | Replicated ledger across nodes; can be permissioned | Type of DLT that stores data in cryptographically chained blocks. :contentReference[oaicite:25]{index=25} |
| Structure | Flexible (not necessarily block-based) | Block-chained structure |
| Consensus | Many types (permissioned algorithms common) | PoW/PoS/NPoS/others |
| Use cases | Enterprise, private networks (Hyperledger, Corda) | Public networks, open value transfer (Bitcoin/Ethereum) :contentReference[oaicite:26]{index=26} |

NFTs vs Fungible Tokens
Key tech concepts
Fungible tokens are interchangeable units (ERC-20 on Ethereum is standard). They represent currency, utility, or governance. ERC-20 defines the standard API and is used by tokens like USDC, USDT, UNI, BNB (BEP-20 on BSC is Ethereum-compatible).
NFTs (non-fungible tokens) are unique on-chain identifiers (pair: contract address + tokenId) ‚Äî common standards: ERC-721, ERC-1155 ‚Äî used to represent unique digital items, collectibles, or tokenized rights. Ownership is recorded on-chain and transferrable; smart contract code controls provenance, royalties (if implemented), and transfer rules. 
Ethereum Improvement Proposals


Ownership & practical effect

On-chain ownership gives provable, tamper-evident provenance and enables on-chain royalty enforcement (if contract supports it) and marketplace automation.

Ownership ‚â† off-chain rights automatically: owning an NFT usually conveys a tokenized right (e.g., a claim, a license, or membership), but underlying copyright/physical property rights depend on the project‚Äôs legal terms. This gap is a frequent source of confusion and legal debate. 
WIRED

Real-world examples (5+), short analysis

Bored Ape Yacht Club (BAYC) ‚Äî Ethereum

Collection of unique PFP NFTs (ERC-721) with strong secondary market on OpenSea; ownership records are on Ethereum and transfers are immutable and visible. Security incidents (phishing/social engineering) show custody risks remain off-chain. 
OpenSea


Axie Infinity (Axies) ‚Äî Ronin (EVM sidechain)

Game NFTs (Axies) and in-game economy; Ronin was built to reduce fees & scale gaming transactions. Demonstrates how a specialized chain can enable massive in-game transactions and new economic models for players. 
AxieInfinity


NBA Top Shot ‚Äî Flow (Dapper Labs)

‚ÄúMoments‚Äù (collectible video highlights) as NFTs on Flow ‚Äî shows an alternative chain (Flow) optimized for collectibles & UX (account model, scalability for consumer adoption). Ownership tracked on Flow; marketplace & developer tooling provided by Dapper. 
NBA Top Shot Developers


Royal / Music NFTs

Royal allows fans to buy streaming royalties or shares of songs as NFTs ‚Äî shows how NFTs can tokenize revenue rights and distribute royalties to fractional owners. Legal/royalty structures matter here. 
Royal


Stablecoins / Fungible tokens (USDT, USDC)

USDT (Tether) and USDC (Circle) are fungible stablecoins used as on-chain money (ERC-20/BEP-20/etc.). They show fungible tokens‚Äô role as medium-of-exchange and settlement in NFT markets and DeFi. Their governance and reserve transparency (attestations) affect trust/regulatory treatment. 
Tether


Governance / Utility token example ‚Äî UNI (Uniswap)

UNI is an ERC-20 governance token; holders vote on protocol upgrades and treasury usage ‚Äî shows tokenized governance vs. tokenized unique assets. 
Uniswap Docs

Takeaway: NFTs add unique digital scarcity, provenance, and programmable sale/royalty mechanics ‚Äî they change the practical meaning of "ownership" for digital goods by enabling verifiable, transferable on-chain claims, but legal rights and custody still require off-chain considerations.

